This is a customizable spring. Not as durable as a steel one, but functional. You can use the customizer to change its dimensions, as well as elastic properties. Feel free to experiment. I opted for this pseudo washer design because I thought a spiral will be less sturdy and wanted a design without rotational tension, so that the spring doesn't have to support more than vertical forces. Parameter election is critical for each type of spring. You can lead to High elastic springs to sturdy low compression springs. Do your proof but remember these are plastic springs and its elastic, thermal, or hardness properties are very dependant of the material used to print them. In general this plastic springs will have a low compression ratio and poor shock resistance due to its plastic composition, but anyway you could make a proof with semiflex like materials, I didn't check out that yet, this will produce mild force springs but shock proof ones...
Also remember that low temperatures will increase a lot the fragility of the plastic.

At print time I recommend to print them horizontal with buildplate support only to alleviate bridge generation and ease of suport removal. Anyway printing it vertically if you can will make a better and more suitable structure for the spring.

Enjoy.

Hint: Those unusable prints you may produce, you can give it to your mother as hair curlers, but warn her about not using a hair dryer with those... ;-)

description.text:
After looking at all the practice pads available, none of my liking were within my prince range.
So after some thinking I came up with this design that allows you to mount a 10" mesh drum head to the shell and tighten it with the rim using the 8 lugs on the sides of the shell, just like most real drums.

The pad exists of 2 parts (3 with the future support added);
-The rim
-The shell
(-The shell with mounting holes available for the future eDrum update)
You will need to print 4 of each (or 2 of each shell type to make ready for the future eDrum update)

In the future I will make a mount in the center to attach a piëzo sensor and 6,3mm jack to make the pad an electric drum pad.

Printer Brand:

Rafts:

Notes:

I have used a 50% infill for the rim to make it more resistant against accidental rim shots/clicks, even more will increase the strength of the rim and make it more durable.

For the shell I used a 25% infill to make still make it fairly light and because it doesn't have to be in contact with the sticks during play.

Finishing

After printing, remove the supports from the underside of the rim parts and from the inside of the lugs on the shell parts.

After removing the support I advise you to sand the upper edge of the shell to make sure the plastic doesn't rip the head.

Assembly

To assemble the rim you will need 4x M4x20mm bolts and 4x M4 nuts..

To assemble the shell you will need 4x M4x20mm bolts, 4x M4x35mm bolts and 8x M4 nuts.

And lastly to actually mount the head (can be mesh or an actual head) you will need 8x M4x35mm bolts and 8x M4 nuts.

Don't forget to tighen the head in a cross pattern to not over tighten it and rip it.

This 3D printed flexible Black Widow spider is printed from Black and Red NinjaFlex. The flexible legs dangle and wiggle when lowered from a string. There are two holes, where red LEDs can be inserted in from the bottom. The red LED's cause the translucent red NinjaFlex to glow with an eerie look. Printed at this scale, it is 10cm across the legs
The 2 red LEDs are wired in series and are connected directly to a 3.7 LiPo battery. So far almost 48 hrs from a single 18650 battery. Note: If you print with the NinjaFlex directly on clean glass, the spiders will stick directly on a window, similar to those vinyl reusable stickers. The NinjaFlex filament is available here: http://www.fennerdrives.com/3D

description.text:
This is a "must have" if you fish... there's nothing worse than seeing discarded fishing line while out fishing or laying in the bottom of your boat. Discarded line can also impose a threat to wildlife. These are a few waste line collectors that can easily be printed to help contain any waste line you may have (or find) while out fishing.

The larger version uses (2) 6/32"x1/8" set screws to hold the barrel in the body while the smaller one just snaps together (be careful as the tabs are fragile though on the smaller version) They both use a piece of the hook portion from some sticky back Velcro to grab the line. A split ring or clip can be inserted into the top while printing.

To use - just hold the line against the hole and then just spin the barrel to wind in the waste line. Works great for long or short pieces of discarded line. When full remove the barrel from the body and cut along the groove of the barrel to remove the old line. Simple as that.

description.text: DO NOT USE the original files; the scaling is wrong due to putative bug in the Inkscape->SCAD conversion plugin (unless I just used it incorrectly; unsure).  See comments for discussion.  I have tried to provide a corrected version as "scalecorrected.scad" and scalecorrected.stl", but these have not yet been tested.  The mis-scaled original files will go away soon.

Original design (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:65374) was SVG for laser cutting, but I had a request for a 3D print SCAD/STL version. I created this using DNewman's Inkscape extension for converting SVG to SCAD, plus a little manual recompositing. See Instructions for more details. (An alternative approach would have been to export from Inkscape as DXF and then use OpenSCAD's extrude function on that, but I didn't test that.)

See the original lasercut version for details on bolts to use, etc.  
I haven't tested this 3D print version.  I set it for 3 mm thickness to match the lasercut acrylic thickness of the Pibow, but this may not work well on some printers; you may want to try a little thicker; it's easy to set in the SCAD file.  
I used smoothness 0.1 in the Inkscape plugin, which is pretty smooth; you can make a much smaller, simpler file with smoothness 0.2 if you want to go back to the original SVG.

title: MPCNC Laser Enclosure
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
After getting my 2W laser working, I realized that the smell of burned wood or other objects does not go away and permeates the shop, so I set about to enclose the Laser and exhaust the fumes outside.

For this project, I used 3/4" sheet insulation purchased from Home Depot as the base material and designed the parts around it.

You will need to print 8 corner pieces and 16 pins. For the hinges, you can print the complete set or individual parts, but you will need at least two sets of hinges to affix the door.

The recessed handle was obtained from Sketchup 3D Warehouse and resized to my needs.

I cut the insulation sheet by hand to the dimensions to fit my MPCNC layout. You will have to notch 1/8" indents for the corner pieces and cutout the recess area with a razor knife and maybe use a Dremel to carefully remove the foam if you don't want the handle to show on the back side of the door.

I have a 12"x12" laser safety sheet on order that I place in the door once it arrives. EDIT: safety glass arrived and is installed. See new photo.

I cut a 4" hole in one panel for the exhaust fan which I obtained from http://www.ebay.com/itm/281349615771?_trksid=p2057872.m2749.l2649&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT

You could also build one if you have a box fan.... http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:42490

I bought a dryer vent for the outside wall and clamps from Home Depot to secure the vent hose.

EDIT: added the doorstop... You need to print 2 of those and glue them to back side to keep the door from swinging inward.

Also, I used liquid nails to glue the recessed handle in place.

Aug 10th 2016 EDIT: I have had one heck of a time finding suitable software to run my Laser. After many hours and trial and error, I ended up modifying a version of Marlin firmware and some python server software to convert images to GCODE.

If you would like to try out the image to GCODE software, you can point your browser to http://flashsolutions.us/img2gcode/index.html and generate your GCODE using a photo. It works very well with inkScape vector graphics saved to PNG or JPG images.

If you would like a copy to run on your PC, it is available on Github at https://github.com/flashsolutions/ along with the Marlin fork that I made to run on the MPCNC with Repetier Host.

title: Folger Tech Kossel P/S Bracket with slot opening for T-Nut Connection

description.text:
I found it easier to connect these brackets to the 2020 Aluminum using a slot on the bracket to slide it onto the M3 screws. While I was at it, I made this bracket more curvy & added ledges to the outside edges for more strength & less plastic. Make sure all the hardware is tight as it is more critical with slotted holes. One of my brackets slipped off when I laid the machine of its side, so I added a 1mm deep M3 screw head countersink to keep the bracket on in case a screw was not tight. I lengthened the bracket at the slot openings by 4mm to give extra length to the slots. I also added a tab at the bottom ot the bracket to rest against the back side of the P/S.

I used M3x10mm Pan Head Screws with the T-Nuts instead of the M3x12mm called for in the build guide. I used the same M4x10mm screws to mount the P/S as called for in the build guide.

I printed these at 50% infill using Yellow eSun PETG.

title: Yet Another Spool Holder
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: This is a simple adjustable & portable spool holder that uses 3d printed parts + a dowel.

The STL files are designed for an 8mm or 5/16" dowel.  Print two base parts, and four rollers at 50% fill or greater.   Make sure your rollers are not lumpy - if they are, use a file or sandpaper to get rid of the bumps.  
Cut two legths of dowel equal to the width of your widest spool plus another 35-40mm or so to account for the dowel holder & roller brim.   Insert the two dowels into one base part, slide the rollers on brim side facing out (so the roller brim is on the outside of the spool) and then put the other base on.  If the plastic is smooth enough, the spool will rotate freely but the rollers may not turn.  You may also have to tape/fasten the holder down to keep it from walking.  
The width can be adjusted just by sliding the base parts closer or farther apart on the dowels.  
The OpenSCAD files are included but note that if you adjust for use with a larger dowel, you may have to hand-modify the material-saving holes & top cut-out (or you can just delete them, per the comments in the file).  
(Updated 10/23: Based on having a spool walk off the rollers, I increased the default brim radius on the rollers to 15mm.  I have found I need to fasten the spool holder down because it's so light.  I'm currently using binder clips at the edge of the table, but tape should work, too.)

This is my attempt at a flexible coupler for joining the 5mm shaft of a stepper to a 3/8 inch leadscrew. It uses 6-32 screws for clamping. The two parts were joined with sugru. Alternatives would include oogoo, flexible hot glue, flexible epoxy or similar. Silicone caulking might work but would require a very long time to cure.

The design files are publicly available from Onshape: https://cad.onshape.com/documents/e06da76270f59cc868ce57d7/w/4e5cc8a1ff89014fd9cf74cd/e/519dcb9ad6b74ed7e0f4b833
I know the CAD files could be better--I'm just learning how to use parametric design. Nevertheless it should be easy to customize. The design includes a few alternatives. Shown are the "clamping stepper coupler" and "clamping leadscrew coupler" parts. These are the ones you would probably want to customize.

Print with high infill for strength. I recommend 80% or higher. I printed this in PETG for toughness.

Not tested with significant misalignment nor heavy load.

title: Replicator Extruder for FLEXIBLE materials - Mk8

description.text:
I put this thing up when I first developed NinjaFlex. I have since left NinjaTek to start Diabase Engineering with a colleague. The Flexion Extruder is our debut product. It can print flexible materials much faster than this design (and much softer materials too).
You can find it here. Flexion Extruder Over the last couple of weeks, I've had a few people contact me about jamming difficulties with flexible filaments. By far, the most critical feature for printing flexible materials is having the filament completely supported between exiting the drive gear (nip) and entering the cold end. This design is just a slight modification of the work done by whpthomas, emmett, whosawhatsis and others. I've just added a small amount of material to prevent the filament from folding under the hobbed portion of the drive gear. It doesn't seem like this would make that much of a difference, but it does...it has allowed me to print materials that my standard Makerbot Mk8 upgrade would not. Edit1: I just added a couple of files for the Arm and Pin that might get you there for the Rep2. I'm kind of flying blind on that design though, b/c at the moment, I only have a Rep1 to work from. Also...I used the following parts from McMaster-Carr:
3mmx10mm Bearing McM P#: 7804K128
M3x8mm FHCS - McM P#: 92125A128

.:BIG HEART:. Heart gears supersized - pump up the volume 600% baby! Emmett's Heart Gears scaled linearly by 180% for maximum loving. The largest part is 12x12x7.5cm. The layout was tweaked and I pushed some polygons for slightly better slicing.

Slicing Because of a known bug in Slic3r, we recommend Skeinforge for this model. (https://github.com/alexrj/Slic3r/issues/198) For smooth transitions over the curves, try 3x perimeters, 4x solid layers and drop your infill to a cheeky 10% to save material. Our print weighed in at 0.6kg. Print the connecting pins as normal and use Multiply to get the number required (4x short, 4x long). Printing Print in gorgeous Cherry Blossom Pink PLA :) There are some pretty bold overhangs, so try a desk fan lightly blowing across your build to avoid curling edges. Minimize warp by printing on Kapton and increase your heated bed by 5-10C. Assembly Gears 2 and 4 are mirrored but not quite identical, so test them for fit (without pins) to check what side they go on (front or back of the heart). The same is true for Gears 5 and 7. We have shared our assembly sequence on Flickr: http://www.flickr.com/photos/faberdashery/

title: Folger Tech Kossel Top Vertex Aluminum 2020 Caps

description.text:
I did not like the idea of the sharp corners protruding from the top, so I designed these little caps to cover them. My vertical 2020's are 20mm above the top, so I made these with 21mm cut on the inside to make sure they fit. I tapered the inside square cut up to a point so there was no problems printing above the cut. You can adjust the height of the inside cut if your verticals are a different height about the vertex by changing the variable Alum_Ht = 21; to the height you need in the openscad file. The Aluminum vertex parts have a nice convenient hole on each side that made it easy to use a screw to hold the top cap in place with a base plate at the bottom of top vertex.

Print one VertexTopCap_Rev5.stl & VertexTopBasePlate_Rev5.stl for each vertex & use 2x M3x30mm screws with locknuts for each cap. There is a VertexTopBasePlate_3x_Rev5.stl file if you want to print all 3 base plates at once.

The way I got verticals to the 20mm above the vertex was to use a 40mm plastic spacer jig (Top40mmJigSpacer.stl) to set the top of the endstops before putting on the top aluminum vertex parts. That way when I put the top on the verticals, they were all within a 1/2mm of 20mm above the top. I included a photo of how I did that.

An openscad file is included for the Top caps & the spacer jig. The Top Cap & Base Plate are created from the same openscad file. On the base plate there is not much plastic holding the 2 sides together, but that was what matched the aluminum vertex profile & they are really only needed to hold the bolts in place from the top.

I printed these with 30% honeycomb infill using to get a better honeycomb looking pattern for visual appeal. You should be able to print these at 20% or less fill.

description.text:
We've laser engraved 2 Samurai Swords with the Hattori Hanzo logo from the film "Kill Bill"!

Using our Speedy 300 flexx, we were able to use a CO2 laser on one sword and a Fiber Laser on the other.

Step 1: Black and White logo

Search the Hattori Hanzo logo (or any logo for the matter and copy and paste it onto a Vector based software (we used CorelDraw)

To convert to black and white press Bitmaps → Mode → Black and White → Line Art

Left click on the left window which will let you preview the conversion.

Adjust as you choose, then press OK.

Step 1: Black and White logo Step 1: Black and White logo Step 1: Black and White logo Step 2: Vector Image

From a raster to a vector, follow these steps Trace Bitmap → Outline Trace → Line Art.

Double lining might occur. To get rid of this by sliding Detail downwards.

To view the original, click and drag the image to the right and you will see the new form and the orignal (on the left).

Step 2: Vector Image Step 2: Vector Image Step 3: Keep the image

Measure the area that the image should be on.

We used the LMM-6000 Black for Metal to coat one samurai sword which will let our CO2 laser engrave.

Shake the can and coat the area.

Step 3: Keep the image Step 4: Organize laser (CO2)

2 different lasers means that there will be 2 laser sources, therefore we need to distinguish them by colour coating them.

Complete the CO2 laser first.

Send the CO2 laser image to the Job Control software.

Make sure the image is sized to the sword.

Select the logo and go to File → Print → select Trotec Engraver for printer.

Go to preferences and adjust the lent hand width accordingly. Then go to My settings → Engrave for Black.

Set the power to 100 and speed to 30, press OK.

Then press Layout → Re position to Center of Page → OK

Step 4: Organize laser (CO2) Step 4: Organize laser (CO2) Step 4: Organize laser (CO2) Step 4: Organize laser (CO2) Step 5: Organize laser (Fiber laser)

Make sure to colour code the this laser a different colour for no confusion.

Change the colour code from black to red by clicking Edit → Find and Replace → Replace Objects → Replace a Color. Set Find to Black and R to 0, G to 0 and B to 0 Set Replace to Red and R to 255, G to 0 and B to 0 Press OK → Finish → Replace All.

Select ghd logo, press File → Print. Do the same to the the CO2 laser. This time we change Black to Skip and for Red choose Engrave FLP.

Power should be set to 100 and speed should be set to 10. Make sure the Hertz is up to 20000 now press OK.

Step 5: Organize laser (Fiber laser) Step 5: Organize laser (Fiber laser) Step 5: Organize laser (Fiber laser) Step 5: Organize laser (Fiber laser) Step 6: Position the swords and setting up the machine

We're using the Speedy 300 flexx laser machine. Since this is a flexx machine, we can complete one with CO2 and one with fiber all in the same job.

*Note: Both swords have be leveled.

Step 7: Locating the sword

For the first sword set the physical laser over the center of the sword. (We did 1 and 1/4" from all sides).

For the Second sword complete the same steps.

Set the corresponding images to the markers, set up the lens and close the lid and press start.

Step 7: Locating the sword Step 7: Locating the sword Step 7: Locating the sword Step 7: Locating the sword Step 8: Wash up

Now all you have to do is wipe the sword down and now you have two samurai swords that are laser engraved! Enjoy!

title: Decorative Corbel / Console Shelf Bracket with built-in french cleat

description.text:
Decorative Corbel / Console Shelving Bracket

Print Dimensions: 6inches x 6inches
French Cleat Angle: 45 degrees
Infill: 25%
Intended Screw Size: #8 (0.16 inch)

Printer Used: Lulzbot Mini

Description

I wanted to try to incorporate some 3D printing into my woodworking hobby with some decorative corbels. Molding simply looks so much better with some kind of architectural elements added to it but buying it from the store gets expensive very quickly.

I finally decided to give CAD a go and picked up Autodesk Fusion 360 because it was free for hobbyists. Using a Lulzbot Mini with maximum print dimensions of 6 inches, I designed this corbel to fit the max printing dimensions of the Lulzbot. Unfortunately, I quickly found out that you'll need to do a lot of tinkering with the standard Cura settings to get the max dimensions; seeing how I'm a novice at all of this I just simply scaled it to the max with the dimensions it allowed me to print. The final product length is something like 5.5 inches by 5.5 inches at it's maximum.

Build

Tools Used

  • Cordless Drill
  • Table Saw with pivoting saw head (alternatively you can use an angled circular saw)

I used a 1/4" ply ripped with a table saw at 45 degrees to build the cleat backing. I then used a stud finder to locate the studs on the wall and drilled the backing plate directly into the wall. This allowed me to cut the length of my shelf at any length and attach the corbels/consoles to it. I found it difficult to attach the shelf onto the bracket without marking the holes precisely; therefore there is room for improvement in the design here.

License

I feel as though this design has room for lots of improvements. From counter-sinks screw holes to easier installation features. Therefore, please feel free to remix this as necessary. You can use it for commercial purposes too but please do attribute as in the creative commons license.
